{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"MySQL Normalization","slug":"mysql-normalization","subject":"MySQL","category":"Database","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["MySQL Database Design"],"learning_objectives":["Understand Redundancy","1NF (First Normal Form)","2NF","3NF","BCNF"],"theory":"## Organizing Data Efficiently\n**Normalization** is the process of organizing data to minimize redundancy (duplicates) and improve integrity.\n\n### The Forms\n1. **1NF (Atomic)**: Each cell contains a single value. No arrays/lists.\n2. **2NF (No Partial Dependency)**: Must be in 1NF. All non-key columns must depend on the *entire* Primary Key.\n3. **3NF (No Transitive Dependency)**: Must be in 2NF. Non-key columns must rely only on the Key, not on other non-key columns.\n\n### Mantra\n'The data depends on the Key, the whole Key, and nothing but the Key.'","syntax":"N/A (Design Concept)","examples":[{"code":"Un-normalized:\nUser | Address\nJohn | NY, USA\n\nNormalized:\nUser Table | Address Table\nJohn       | ID 1 -> NY, USA","output":"N/A","explanation":"Splitting data into linked tables reduces duplication if John has multiple addresses."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Over-normalization.","correction":"Creating too many tables leads to complex, slow queries (too many JOINs). Sometimes Denormalization is needed for performance.","example":"N/A"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is Denormalization?","answer":"Intentionally adding redundancy (e.g., storing 'count' in a parent table) to avoid expensive joins/calculations on read.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[],"real_world_use_cases":[],"exam_notes":["1NF: Atomic values.","2NF: Whole PK.","3NF: Nothing but PK.","Reduces Update Anomalies."],"summary":"Normalization reduces data redundancy and improves data integrity, albeit at the cost of query complexity (Joins).","order":17},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"mysql-introduction-to-databases","path":"content/mysql/mysql-introd